📝 Step-by-Step Implementation Logic
Step 1: The "Sliding Window" (The 30-Frame Queue)
Your live camera runs at roughly 30 frames per second. Your LSTM expects exactly a 30-frame sequence to make a prediction. Instead of waiting 1 second, recording, and then predicting (which causes terrible start-stop lag), you will create a continuous queue.
Initialize a deque with maxlen=30.
Every time the webcam grabs a new frame, instantly calculate your Kinematic Math (Centered Coordinates + Joint Angles), and push that flat array into the queue.
Because maxlen=30, the oldest frame at the back of the queue is automatically dropped as new frames enter.
The Result: Your AI always has access to a rolling "last 1 second of continuous time."
Step 2: The Continuous Prediction Engine
Every single time a new frame enters the Queue, you ask the AI to evaluate the current window.
Shape the Data: Expand the dimensions of your 30-frame queue to match the 3D Tensor shape your model needs: [1, 30, Features].
Predict: Pass this sequence into model.predict().
The Overlap Problem: If you sign "Help" over 30 frames, the sliding window will capture fragments of that sign for 30 consecutive loops. A raw AI might output the word "Help" 15 times in a row as the gesture passes through the window. We fix this in Step 3.
Step 3: Gesture Spotting & State Logic (The Core Secret)
You must write hard-coded state logic to filter out the spam and figure out the exact boundaries of a word.
Confidence Thresholding: Only accept a prediction if the AI's Softmax probability is $>85\%$.
The "Same Word" Filter: Create a tracking variable (e.g., last_predicted_word). If the AI predicts "Help" with 95% confidence, check if last_predicted_word is already "Help". If it is, ignore it to prevent stuttering.
The "Neutral" Reset: This is exactly why you trained a "Neutral" class! Tell the system: "Do not allow any new word to be added to the sentence until the AI sees the user drop their hands to the 'Neutral' pose." This acts as the "spacebar" between words, forcing the logic to acknowledge the end of a sign.
Sentence Appending: When a valid, new word is detected, append it to a string called current_sentence (e.g., "HELLO " + "PLEASE " + "HELP ").
Step 4: The Final Subtitle UI
UI Overlay: Use OpenCV to draw a semi-transparent black rectangle at the bottom of the video feed. Inside this box, boldly render the current_sentence variable. This creates a highly professional "Subtitles" look.
Clear the Board: Create a keyboard trigger (e.g., pressing 'C') or a timeout logic (e.g., 5 seconds of continuous "Neutral" pose) to empty the current_sentence variable so the user can start a new sentence.
Metrics Display: Render your FPS and Inference Latency (ms) in the top corner of the screen to explicitly prove to your evaluators that your engineered pipeline runs flawlessly on edge hardware.

